1 Imagini, chi bene intender cupe 2 quel ch’i’ or vidi—e ritegna l’image, 3 mentre ch’io dico, come ferma rupe—,
4 quindici stelle che ’n diverse plage 5 lo ciel avvivan di tanto sereno 6 che soperchia de l’aere ogne compage;
7 imagini quel carro a cu’ il seno 8 basta del nostro cielo e notte e giorno, 9 sì ch’al volger del temo non vien meno;
10 imagini la bocca di quel corno 11 che si comincia in punta de lo stelo 12 a cui la prima rota va dintorno,
13 aver fatto di sé due segni in cielo, 14 qual fece la figliuola di Minoi 15 allora che sentì di morte il gelo;
16 e l’un ne l’altro aver li raggi suoi, 17 e amendue girarsi per maniera 18 che l’uno andasse al primo e l’altro al poi;
19 e avrà quasi l’ombra de la vera 20 costellazione e de la doppia danza 21 che circulava il punto dov’ io era:
22 poi ch’è tanto di là da nostra usanza, 23 quanto di là dal mover de la Chiana 24 si move il ciel che tutti li altri avanza.

query.result:
1 Images, who well understand the dark 2 that which I now saw—and retain the image, 3 while I speak, like a firm cliff—,
4 fifteen stars that in different plains 5 the sky enlivened with so much serenity 6 that overwhelms every companion of the air;
7 imagine that carriage to which the breast 8 is enough of our sky and night and day, 9 so that at the turning of time it does not lessen;
10 imagine the mouth of that horn 11 which begins at the tip of the star 12 to which the first wheel goes around,
13 having made of itself two signs in the sky, 14 as the daughter of Minoi did 15 then when she felt death’s chill;
16 and one in the other having its rays, 17 and both turning in such a way 18 that one would go to the first and the other to the later;
19 and will have almost the shadow of the true 20 constellation and of the double dance 21 that circled the point where I was:
22 since it is so far beyond our custom, 23 as far beyond the movement of the Plain 24 the sky moves that surpasses all the others.

28 He completed the singing and turned its measure;  
29 and to wait for us those holy lights,  
30 gladdening himself with care in care.

52 That which does not die and that which can die 53 is nothing but the splendor of that idea 54 which gives birth, loving, to our Lord;
55 because that living light that so mea 56 from its shining, which does not separate 57 from him nor from the love that interposes to them,
58 by its goodness its radiance gathers, 59 almost mirrored, in nine existences, 60 eternally remaining itself one.

